<section>
  <title>Hermite Interpolation</title>

  <introduction>
    <p>
      In the previous section, we studied polynomial interpolation in which a polynomial passes through the points <m>(x_{0},f_{0}), (x_{1},f_{1}),\ldots, (x_{n},f_{n})</m>.
      In this section, we consider the polynomial also satisfies the derivative conditions <m>(x_{0},f'_{0})</m>, <m>(x_{1},f'_{1})</m>, <m>\ldots</m>, <m>(x_{n},f'_{n})</m>.
      This is called <em>Hermite Interpolation</em>.
    </p>

    <p>
      Consider an example in which a polynomial <m>P(x)</m> needs to satisfy the points <m>(0,0)</m> and <m>(2,0)</m> as well having a slope of 1 at <m>x=0</m> and a slope of <m>-1</m> at <m>x=2</m>.
      Visually, this is:
    </p>

    <figure xml:id="fig-hermite-example">
      <caption></caption>
      <image width="70%">
        <shortdescription>
        </shortdescription>
        <latex-image>
      <![CDATA[
      \begin{tikzpicture}
\draw[->] (-2.5,0) -- (2.5,0) node [above right] {$x$}; \foreach \x in {-2,-1,1,2} \draw (\x,0.1) -- (\x,-0.1) node [below] {\x};
 \draw[->] (0,-2.5) -- (0,2.5) node [above right] {$y$};
\foreach \y in {-2,-1,1,2} \draw (0.1,\y) -- (-0.1,\y) node [left] {\y};
\draw (-0.25,-0.25) -- (0.25,0.25);
\draw (1.75,0.25) -- (2.25,-0.25);
\foreach \x/\y in {0/0,2/0} \fill (\x,\y) circle [radius=2pt];
\end{tikzpicture}
      ]]>
        </latex-image>
      </image>
    </figure>

    <p>
      where the lines in the plot are the tangent lines to the polynomial.
      This polynomial must be at most order 3 (with 4 unknowns) to satisfy the 4 conditions.
      A crude way to proceed would be to write:
      <me>
        \begin{aligned}P(x)\amp = a_{0} + a_{1}x + a_{2} x^{2} + a_{3} x^{3} \\
        \text{and its derivative}\qquad\qquad \amp \\
        P'(x)\amp = a_{1} + 2a_{2} x + 3a_{3} x^{2}\end{aligned}
      </me>
    </p>

    <p>
      Applying <m>P(0)=0</m> and <m>P'(0)=1</m> leads to <m>a_{0}=0</m> and <m>a_{1}=1</m>.
      If we set <m>P(2)=0</m> and <m>P'(2) = -1</m> we get:
      <me>
        \begin{aligned}P(2)\amp = (2) + a_{2} (2)^{2} + a_{3} (2)^{3} \\ P'(2)\amp = 1 + 2 a_{2} (2) + 3 a_{3} (2)^{2}\end{aligned}
      </me>
      and solve for <m>a_{2}</m> and <m>a_{3}</m> (using some linear algebra) results in <m>a_{2}=-1/2</m> and <m>a_{3}=0</m>, thus the polynomial is:
      <me>
        \begin{aligned}P(x)\amp = x -\frac{1}{2}x^{2}\end{aligned}
      </me>
    </p>

    <p>
      In short, Hermite polynomials exist and are unique much like Lagrange polynomials.
      The proofs are similar to that shown in <xref ref="sect-lagrange-interp"/> however a bit more complicated in that the form of the interpolation is more complicated due to the requirement that the derivative needs to match.
      See Burden and Faires, Burden:2004fk for more information about this.
    </p>
  </introduction>


  <subsection>
    <title>Hermite Interpolation Implementation</title>

    <p>
      The form presented above is not a simple way to find the polynomial coefficients as the degree of the polynomial gets large.
      Instead, we proceed in a way which closely follows that of Newton Divided Differences.
    </p>

    <p>
      The idea behind using Newton Divided Differences in Hermite interpolation is as follows.
      Let <m>z_{2i}=x_{i}</m> and <m>z_{2i+1}=x_{i}</m> for <m>i=0,1,\ldots, n</m>.
      However some of the difference formulas will have the form:
      <me>
        \begin{aligned}f[z_{0},z_{1}]=f[x_{0},x_{0}]\amp = \frac{f[x_{0}]-f[x_{0}]}{x_{0}-x_{0}}\end{aligned}
      </me>
      which has the form <m>0/0</m>.
      When this situation arises, let <m>f[x_{i},x_{i}]=f'(x_{i})</m>.
    </p>

    <p>
      The Newton Divide Difference table for two points <m>x_{0}</m> and <m>x_{1}</m> (or the four points <m>z_{0},z_{1},z_{2},z_{3}</m>).
    </p>

    <tabular>
      <row>
        <cell> </cell>
        <cell> </cell>
        <cell>First divided</cell>
        <cell>Second divided</cell>
      </row>

      <row>
        <cell> <m>z</m> </cell>
        <cell> <m>f(z)</m> </cell>
        <cell>difference</cell>
        <cell>difference</cell>
      </row>

      <row>
        <cell> </cell>
      </row>

      <row>
        <cell> <m>z_{0}=x_{0}</m> </cell>
        <cell> <m>f[z_{0}]=f(x_{0})</m> </cell>
      </row>

      <row>
        <cell> </cell>
        <cell> </cell>
        <cell> <m>f[z_{0},z_{1}]=f[x_{0},x_{0}]=f'(x_{0})</m> </cell>
      </row>

      <row>
        <cell> <m>z_{1}=x_{0}</m> </cell>
        <cell> <m>f[z_{1}]=f(x_{0})</m> </cell>
        <cell> </cell>
        <cell> <m>\displaystyle f[z_{0},z_{1},z_{2}] = \frac{f[z_{1},z_{2}]-f[z_{0},z_{1}]}{z_{2}-z_{0}}</m> </cell>
      </row>

      <row>
        <cell> </cell>
        <cell> </cell>
        <cell> <m>\displaystyle f[z_{1},z_{2}] = \frac{f[z_{2}]-f[z_{1}]}{z_{2}-z_{1}}</m> </cell>
      </row>

      <row>
        <cell> <m>z_{2} = x_{1}</m> </cell>
        <cell> <m>f[z_{2}]=f(x_{1})</m> </cell>
        <cell> </cell>
        <cell> <m>\displaystyle f[z_{1},z_{2},z_{3}] = \frac{f[z_{2},z_{3}]-f[z_{1},z_{2}]}{z_{3}-z_{1}}</m> </cell>
      </row>

      <row>
        <cell> </cell>
        <cell> </cell>
        <cell> <m>\displaystyle f[z_{2},z_{3}] = f[x_{1},x_{1}]=f'(x_{1})</m> </cell>
      </row>

      <row>
        <cell> <m>x_{3} = x_{1}</m> </cell>
        <cell> <m>f[z_{3}]=f(x_{1})</m> </cell>
      </row>
    </tabular>

    <p>
      If additional points are needed, the divided difference table can be continued in a similar manner.
    </p>

    <example>
      <statement>
        <p>
          Use the Newton Divided Difference table to produce the Hermite Polynomial that satisfies <m>P(0)=0, P(2)=0, P'(0)=1</m> and <m>P'(2)=-1</m>.
        </p>

        <p>
        </p>

        <p>
          First let <m>z_{0}=z_{1}=x_{0}=0</m> and <m>z_{2}=z_{3}=x_{1}=2</m>.
        </p>

        <tabular>
          <row>
            <cell> <m>z</m> </cell>
            <cell> <m>f(z)</m> </cell>
            <cell>1st D.D.</cell>
            <cell>2nd D.D.</cell>
            <cell>3rd D.D.</cell>
          </row>

          <row>
            <cell> </cell>
          </row>

          <row>
            <cell> <m>0</m> </cell>
            <cell>0</cell>
            <cell> </cell>
          </row>

          <row>
            <cell> </cell>
            <cell> </cell>
            <cell> <m>\boxed{1}</m> </cell>
          </row>

          <row>
            <cell> <m>0</m> </cell>
            <cell> <m>0</m> </cell>
            <cell> </cell>
            <cell> <m>-1/2</m> </cell>
          </row>

          <row>
            <cell> </cell>
            <cell> </cell>
            <cell> <m>0</m> </cell>
            <cell> </cell>
            <cell> <m>0</m> </cell>
          </row>

          <row>
            <cell> <m>2</m> </cell>
            <cell> <m>0</m> </cell>
            <cell> </cell>
            <cell> <m>1/2</m> </cell>
          </row>

          <row>
            <cell> </cell>
            <cell> </cell>
            <cell> <m>\boxed{-1}</m> </cell>
          </row>

          <row>
            <cell> <m>2</m> </cell>
            <cell> <m>0</m> </cell>
            <cell> </cell>
          </row>
        </tabular>

        <p>
          where the two boxed values are the derivative values given in the problem.
        </p>

        <p>
          And as we saw in Newton divided difference, we produce a polynomial based on the top diagonal elements of the table.
          The only difference is recall that since there are two <m>z=0</m> terms, there will be a <m>(z-0)^{2}</m> term as well.
          The Hermite Polynomial will be:
          <me>
            H(z) = 0 + 1 \cdot z - \frac{1}{2}z^{2} + 0 \cdot z^{2} (z-2)
          </me>
          or writing it back in terms of <m>x</m>:
          <me>
            H(x) = x - \frac{1}{2}x^{2}
          </me>
          which is the same as seen above.
        </p>
      </statement>
    </example>

    <p>
      The next example applies this technique to finding a Hermite polynomial to <m>\sin x</m> on <m>[0,\pi]</m>.
    </p>

    <example>
      <statement>
        <p>
          Find the Hermite Polynomial that satisfies both the function value and derivative of <m>f(x)=\sin x</m> for <m>x_{0}=0, x_{1}=\pi/2</m> and <m>x_{2}=\pi</m>.
        </p>
      </statement>

      <solution>
        <p>
          We will first produce a Divided Difference table:
        </p>

        <tabular>
          <row>
            <cell> <m>z</m> </cell>
            <cell> <m>f(z)</m> </cell>
            <cell>1st D.D.</cell>
            <cell>2nd D.D.</cell>
            <cell>3rd D.D.</cell>
            <cell>4th D.D.</cell>
            <cell>5th D.D.</cell>
          </row>

          <row>
            <cell> </cell>
          </row>

          <row>
            <cell>0</cell>
            <cell>0</cell>
          </row>

          <row>
            <cell> </cell>
            <cell> </cell>
            <cell> <m>\boxed{1}</m> </cell>
          </row>

          <row>
            <cell>0</cell>
            <cell>0</cell>
            <cell> </cell>
            <cell> <m>\dfrac{4-2\pi}{\pi^2}</m> </cell>
          </row>

          <row>
            <cell> </cell>
            <cell> </cell>
            <cell> <m>2/\pi</m> </cell>
            <cell> </cell>
            <cell> <m>\dfrac{4\pi-16}{\pi^3}</m> </cell>
          </row>

          <row>
            <cell> <m>\pi/2</m> </cell>
            <cell>1</cell>
            <cell> </cell>
            <cell> <m>-\dfrac{4}{\pi^2}</m> </cell>
            <cell> </cell>
            <cell> <m>\dfrac{16-4\pi}{\pi^4}</m> </cell>
          </row>

          <row>
            <cell> </cell>
            <cell> </cell>
            <cell> <m>\boxed{0}</m> </cell>
            <cell> </cell>
            <cell>0</cell>
            <cell> </cell>
            <cell>0</cell>
          </row>

          <row>
            <cell> <m>\pi/2</m> </cell>
            <cell>1</cell>
            <cell> </cell>
            <cell> <m>-\dfrac{4}{\pi^2}</m> </cell>
            <cell> </cell>
            <cell> <m>\dfrac{16-4\pi}{\pi^4}</m> </cell>
          </row>

          <row>
            <cell> </cell>
            <cell> </cell>
            <cell> <m>-2/\pi</m> </cell>
            <cell> </cell>
            <cell> <m>\dfrac{16-4\pi}{\pi^3}</m> </cell>
          </row>

          <row>
            <cell> <m>\pi</m> </cell>
            <cell>0</cell>
            <cell> </cell>
            <cell> <m>\dfrac{2\pi-4}{\pi^2}</m> </cell>
          </row>

          <row>
            <cell> </cell>
            <cell> </cell>
            <cell> <m>\boxed{-1}</m> </cell>
          </row>

          <row>
            <cell> <m>\pi</m> </cell>
            <cell>0</cell>
          </row>
        </tabular>

        <p>
          And then read the Hermite polynomial off the top diagonal row:
          <me>
            \begin{aligned}H(x)\amp = 0 + 1 \cdot x + \frac{4-2\pi}{\pi^{2}}\cdot x^{2} + \frac{4\pi-16}{\pi^{3}}\cdot x^{2} (x-\pi/2) \\\amp \qquad + \frac{16-4\pi}{\pi^{4}}\cdot x^{2} (x-\pi/2)^{2}\end{aligned}
          </me>
        </p>

        <p>
          A plot both the polynomial and the sine function is:
        </p>

        <figure xml:id="fig-hermite-sine">
          <caption></caption>
          <image>
            <shortdescription>
            </shortdescription>
            <latex-image>
      <![CDATA[
      \begin{tikzpicture}[scale=3]
\draw[->] (-0.5,0) -- (3.5,0) node [above right] {$x$};
\foreach \x/\lab in {0.785/{\frac{\pi}{4}},1.57/{\frac{\pi}{2}},2.356/{\frac{3\pi}{4}},3.142/{\pi}} \draw (\x,0.1) -- (\x,-0.1) node [below] {$\lab$};
 \draw[->] (0,-1.25) -- (0,1.25) node [above right] {$y$};
\foreach \y in {-1,1} \draw (0.1,\y) -- (-0.1,\y) node [left] {\y};
\draw[<->] plot [domain=-0.1:3.3] (\x,{sin(\x r)});
\draw[<->,dashed] plot [domain=-0.3:3.3,samples=500, smooth] (\x,{\x+(4-2*pi)*\x*\x/(pi*pi) + (4*pi-16)/pow(pi,3)*\x*\x*(\x-pi/2)+(16-4*pi)/pow(pi,4)*pow(\x,2)*pow(\x-pi/2,2)});
\end{tikzpicture}
      ]]>
            </latex-image>
          </image>
        </figure>

        <p>
          and this shows that to the visual eye, they appear the same.
          If we plot the absolute value of the difference:
        </p>

        <figure xml:id="fig-hermite-sine-error">
          <caption></caption>
          <image>
            <shortdescription>
            </shortdescription>
            <latex-image>
      <![CDATA[
      \begin{tikzpicture}[xscale=3,yscale=3]
\draw[->] (-0.5,0) -- (3.5,0) node [above right] {$x$};
\foreach \x/\lab in {0.785/{\frac{\pi}{4}},1.57/{\frac{\pi}{2}},2.356/{\frac{3\pi}{4}},3.142/{\pi}} \draw (\x,0.1) -- (\x,-0.1) node [below] {$\lab$};
 \draw[->] (0,-0.1) -- (0,0.4) node [above right] {$y$};
\foreach \y/\lab in {0.1/0.001,0.2/0.002,0.3/0.003} \draw (0.02,\y) -- (-0.02,\y) node [left] {$\lab$};
\draw[<->] plot [domain=-0.3:3.3,smooth,samples=500] (\x,{100*abs(sin(\x r) - (\x+(4-2*pi)*\x*\x/(pi*pi) + (4*pi-16)/pow(pi,3)*\x*\x*(\x-pi/2)+(16-4*pi)/pow(pi,4)*pow(\x,2)*pow(\x-pi/2,2) ))} );
\end{tikzpicture}
      ]]>
            </latex-image>
          </image>
        </figure>

        <p>
          you can see that the error seems to be bounded by 0.003.
          There are error bounds for Hermite polynomials, however we will not cover them here.
        </p>
      </solution>
    </example>
  </subsection>
</section>